TOTAL_PAGES: 1: $1.1B deal: Teleflex buys Calif. medical device maker
column7: Medical device maker Teleflex Inc. entered into an agreement Tuesday to buy NeoTract for $1.1 billion.  NeoTract, based in Pleasanton, Calif., is the developer of the Urolift, a Food and Drug Administration-approved implantable device for treating lower urinary tract symptoms in patients with enlarged prostates.  Founded in 2004, NeoTract had revenues of about $51 million in 2016.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: Device maker Teleflex boosts urology business with NeoTract buy
column7: Medical device maker Teleflex Inc  said on Tuesday it would buy privately held NeoTract Inc in its  second billion-dollar deal in the past nine months, to  strengthen its portfolio of urology devices.  Teleflex, which also makes emergency care, respiratory and  cardiac devices, said the deal's value could rise to $1.1  billion based on sales of NeoTract's sole device, UroLift  System, which targets a market worth more than $30 billion.  The deal is Teleflex's 23rd since 2008, according to Thomson  Reuters data, and comes after its $1 billion acquisition of  Vascular Solutions in December for its minimally invasive  coronary and vascular devices.
